40 (iii) Has family currently receiving or during the term of such family's eligibility
41 previously received state funded adoption services as provided for in Code
42 Section 49-5-8; or
43 (iv) Was adopted from the permanent legal custody of and placed for adoption by the
44 Division of Family and Children Services following the child's fourteenth birthday,
45 including any such individual who, at the time of application to an eligible
46 postsecondary institution, resides outside of Georgia due to such placement; or
47 (v) Is a former foster child who was in the custody of the Division of Family and
48 Children Services for at least six months after reaching the age of 14 years; or
49 (vi) Is an aging foster child as such term is defined in Code Section 48-7-29.24.
50 (3) 'Georgia Foster Care Scholarship' or 'grant' means the grant provided for in this part.
51 (4) 'Grant coordinating organization' means a nonprofit organization that is a qualified
52 organization as such term is defined in Code Section 48-7-29.24 and has, within the prior
53 calendar year, made qualified expenditures as such term is defined in such Code section
54 for the direct benefit of no fewer than 100 aging foster children as such term is defined
55 in such Code section.
56 20-3-672.
57 (a) Subject to appropriations made specifically for the purposes of this part, the Georgia
58 Student Finance Authority shall establish the Georgia Foster Care Scholarship program to
59 provide grants on a per-semester basis to eligible students for undergraduate level
60 postsecondary education at eligible postsecondary institutions.
61 (b) The Georgia Student Finance Authority shall be authorized to provide for eligibility
62 criteria and grant amounts as determined to be the most appropriate for particular eligible
63 postsecondary institutions and its student population in accordance with this part and the
64 rules and regulations of the Georgia Student Finance Authority. The Georgia Student
